## Risk analysis (session 3)

Startup crash `Can't unsafeBitCast between types of different sizes`:
NOT reachable from tree-traversal logging code. Full repo audit:

* `grep -rn unsafeBitCast --include='*.swift' code/` returns three
  hits, all in `FSEventsBridge.swift` (lines 191, 193, 205), and all
  three are inside `//` comments documenting the historical fix.
  There is no live `unsafeBitCast` call anywhere in the Swift sources.
* `Unmanaged.fromOpaque` is used in `FSEventsBridge.swift` only, and
  only on opaque pointers handed in by the FSEvents C API after a
  `CFGetTypeID` discriminator check. Single-pointer object refs —
  no size-mismatch path.
* `withMemoryRebound` / `withUnsafeBytes` / `bindMemory` callsites:
  `ExternalToolIPC.swift` (sockaddr / UInt8 — sized correctly),
  `FileSystemProbe.swift::f_fstypename` (CChar — sized correctly).
  None are in tree-traversal logging code.

So the runtime fatal error is being raised by a DIFFERENT subsystem.
Most likely candidates (flagged for the owning agents, NOT fixed
here because they are out of scope for this plan):

* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/PollingScopeWatcher.swift` —
  session 2 already noted this file has compile errors against
  `Darwin.stat`. A wrong-sized `stat` interop is a textbook trigger.
* `code/Sources/ImageGlass/FileSystem/FileSystemProbe.swift:154` —
  `withUnsafeBytes(of: &st.f_fstypename) { ... bindMemory(to: CChar.self) }`.
  Sized correctly today, but this is the same family of API surface;
  flagged as adjacent risk.

Per-node crash audit of `DirectoryTree.swift` (the file this plan
owns):

* No `unsafeBitCast`.
* No `try!`.
* No `as!` casts.
* No `fatalError`.
* No force-unwrap (`!.` / trailing `!`).
* No `Unmanaged` / opaque-pointer interop.
* `nodeCountSplit` is recursive; stack-overflow risk only if depth
  ≫ typical filesystem (~50). The walker constructs the tree by
  recursing the same way, so any tree the walker can build, this
  helper can also count.
* `logTraversalSummary` is total — no precondition, no optional
  chain, no early failure. Safe to call on any subtree.

Conclusion: the helper and its supporting code are crash-clean. The
startup fatal error is upstream of this plan's surface.

## Changes made (session 3)

None. The crash-audit pass found no force-unwrap, no `try!`, no
`unsafeBitCast`, no `Unmanaged` mismatch, and no recursion-overflow
risk on realistic filesystem trees in the code this plan owns. The
session-2 implementation is still in place and still uncalled.

Demotion / deletion note (per the runbook prompt): the named
instrument is spec-required by `docs/performance.mdx` §5.3, and the
helper is a one-shot emitter (not a per-node trace), so there is
nothing to demote to debug-level. The chattiness problem
(`Tree.Traverse.Log` at 888K instances in the snapshot) was caused
by the deleted per-node `traverseAndLog` pattern, not by this
helper. Keeping the API in place; ready for the
`DirectoryTreeWalker` agent to wire in a single call inside the
existing post-walk block.
